text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Expansion: ESL Classes %0a:Author: sgangu%0a:Original: [[Articles.GivingAnExamInIndianEnglish|GivingAnExamInIndianEnglish]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.Mihir_D|Mihir_D]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 21.04.2021 - 20:30%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-001741-612670#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 17:17-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-001741-612670#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI definitely think that Indian English formed because of translating our first language directly into the closest words in English. There is no way for non-Native English speakers to know that the alarm going "off" means that it is actually ringing. Since English was not my first language, I was placed in English as a second language (ESL) classes in elementary school primarily for speaking Indian english. I remember once I had spent enough time in school, my English become like that of a native speaker and I no longer used literal translations from Telugu. It was at this point that I was taken out of ESL classes, but I sort of didn't really understand the need for them in the first place. Most non standard American English is pretty understandable and ESL classes should not be for those who simply just speak English in a different way. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
